properties.incident title: SITUATION UPDATE - Ferguson/Meers/Indiahoma  Fire - Monday 5p
properties.description:
SITUATION UPDATE - Ferguson/Meers Fire - Monday 5p

Written by Chris Killmer - Public Information Officer
Monday, 05 September 2011 21:52
Monday, Sept 5 – 5pm

The Ferguson Fire/Meers Fire continues to grow due to extreme drought conditions, steep and rugged terrain, and gusty winds.  Late yesterday the fire made a significant run to the southwest across Highway 49 and into the Charons Garden Wilderness and resulted in new evacuations.

Crews continue to actively fight fire in an effort to contain this very large fire.

Refuge officials are currently working to obtain an accurate burn area of this fire.

EVACUATIONS

Approximately 14 homes and the Treasure Lake Job Corps Center in the Indiahoma area were evacuated. The evacuation area includes residents from the intersection of NW 267th Street & NW Cross Road, north to Oklahoma 49 and east to the Refuge boundary.

ROAD CLOSURES

State Highway 115 is closed north to Meer from its junction with State Highway 49. Highway 49 is closed from the Junction of Highway 115 at the WichitaNational Wildlife Refuge Visitor Center west to Road 267. Indiahoma Road is closed from the refuge boundary north to Highway 49.

DAMAGES

NO reports of damages or destroyed homes in the threatened area.

FIRE OPERATIONS

Numerous fire crews from across the state continue their efforts to contain the fire.

INJURIES

NO injuries reported

Additional updates as needed.

properties.incident title: SITUATION UPDATE - Indiahoma Fire - Monday 6a
properties.description:
SITUATION UPDATE - Indiahoma Fire - Monday 6a

Written by Chris Killmer - Public Information Officer
Monday, 05 September 2011 11:56
Monday, Sept 5 – 6am

Fire and county road crews continue to battle grass fires with little or no sleep over the past several days.

Approximately 65 fire and law personnel from Comanche County, as well as fire task forces from McClain and Tillman counties are making preparations in response to a large grass fire in the Charons Garden Wilderness area on the Wichita Mountain Wildlife Refuge.  Crews were notified about 6pm Sunday to stand by as the fire was approaching Refuge boundaries.

EVACUATIONS

121 students and 4 supervisors from Treasure Lake Job Corps have been evacuated to Indiahoma Public Schools.

Approximately 14 homes evacuated. The area includes residents from the intersection of NW 267th Street & NW Cross Road, north to Oklahoma 49 and east to the Refuge boundary.

FIRE OPERATIONS

Comanche County District 3 (western district) graders are currently creating fire breaks around the evacuated homes.  Fire crews are also working with county graders to create a controlled fire to protect structures and contain the fire as it comes off the Refuge.

WEATHER CONDITIONS

7a – Temp-56, Winds-N 10mph, Humidity-53%

10a - Temp-65, Winds-NE 10-15mph, Humidity-38%

1p - Temp-78, Winds-NE 15-20mph Gusts-30mph, Humidity-25%

INJURIES

NO injuries reported

Additional updates as needed.

properties.incident title: Meers Fire Update, 0400am Sunday 9/4
properties.description:
SITUATION UPDATE - Meers Fire - Sunday 4a

Written by Chris Killmer - Public Information Officer
Sunday, 04 September 2011 09:28
Saturday, Sept 4 – 4am

Fire crews are minimizing staff to monitor the grass fire in northwestern Comanche County which has destroyed 11 homes and affected more than 30,000 acres.  A cold front which moved into the area around 12am brought a minimal amount of precipitation and higher humidity levels to help calm the fire.  With expectations of the front, fire personnel set controlled fire lines in order to allow the winds to push the fire into already burned areas.

Fire and law personnel from across the State and northern Texas responded to the massive wildfire which began Thursday afternoon near Oklahoma 49 on the Wichita Mountains Wildlife Refuge.  Refuge officials have not released a cause of fire.

DAMAGES

11 total homes were destroyed (10 - Mountain Village, 1 – Post Oak Rd & North Dr).  An unknown number of outbuildings, barns and storage buildings have been destroyed.

Approximately 32,500 acres (50 square miles) have been affected.

Crews were able to preserve most structures in Camp Y’Shua, including the several homes which are in that area.

INJURIES

One law enforcement personnel was transported to the hospital Friday evening due to smoke inhalation.  One firefighter was transported to the hospital Saturday night after falling from a truck and receiving a concussion.  Several minor injuries were reported, those being treated and released.

EVACUATIONS

Evacuations will be re-evaluated at daylight.

Approximately 100 homes remain evacuated.

60 – Mountain Village and area
30 – Mount Sheridan Estates
10 – Meers Store area
Final Update.
